-- Colombia, Peru, Argentina, Chile: Latin America Bond and Currency Preview
-- Andrea Jaramillo
-- 2010-04-09T04:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-08/colombia-peru-argentina-chile-latin-america-bond-and-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Latin American local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous day’s session.  
 Colombia: Minutes of the central bank’s March 26 monetary
policy meeting are set to be released today. Policy makers last
month left the overnight lending rate unchanged at a record low
of 3.5 percent.  
 The peso rose 0.4 percent to 1,922.80 per dollar.  
 The yield on Colombia’s benchmark 11 percent bonds due July
2020 was unchanged at 8.59 percent, according to Colombia’s
stock exchange.  
 Peru: The trade surplus widened to $580 million in February
from $362 million the previous month, according to the median
estimate of three economists surveyed by Bloomberg News. The
national statistics agency is expected to release the trade
report sometime today.  
 The sol was little changed at 2.8365 per dollar.  
 The yield on Peru’s 8.6 percent bond maturing August 2017
rose one basis point, or 0.01 percentage point, to 5.14 percent,
according to Citigroup Inc.’s unit in Lima.  
 Other prices in Latin American markets:  
 Argentina: The peso was little changed at 3.8773 per
dollar.  
 The yield on the country’s dollar bonds due in 2015 fell 12
basis points to 11.52 percent, according to JPMorgan Chase & Co.  
 Brazil: The real strengthened 0.3 percent to 1.7766 per
dollar.  
 The yield on the zero-coupon, real-denominated bond due in
January 2011 rose three basis points to 10.49 percent, according
to Bloomberg prices.  
 Chile: The peso was little changed at 516.25 per dollar.  
 The yield for a basket of Chile’s 10-year peso bonds in
inflation-linked currency units, called unidades de fomento,
rose two basis points to 3.2 percent, according to Bloomberg
composite prices.  
 Mexico: The peso gained 0.5 percent to 12.2299 per dollar.  
 The yield on Mexico’s 10 percent bond due December 2024
fell five basis points to 7.81 percent, according to Banco
Santander SA.  
